top_comments: Alternative title: Bodybuilders discover calisthenics

Been doing deficit push ups with elevated feet for a few months now. Couple hints: 1) if using yoga blocks (like in the video, I recommend them) use your fists instead of the open hand. It will give you about 2 more inches for deficit movement, without having to strain your neck back . Also reduces the strain on your wrists since they are at a more severe angle than normal. With the foam yoga blocks, you won't hurt your knuckles. 2) If you do this at home, do it in front of the stairs. You can adjust the angle by changing which stair tread you use. 3) Use a weight vest for overloading. Once you do this for a while, you'll start blowing out the # of reps and will need to increase the load to keep seeing growth. You can use the vest for overloading a lot of other body weight exercises too, like squats.

When measured by weight (like in grams or ounces), fine sea salt and kosher salt have the same sodium content since they're both just sodium chloride (NaCl). The only difference comes when measuring by volume (like teaspoons) because kosher salt's larger flakes take up more space. 1 tsp of fine salt holds more crystals than 1 tsp of kosher salt, so you'd get more sodium that way. pDF_GUIeuo4.title: How I Built a MASSIVE 100kg Lifting Drone
top_comments: Bro, go to settings and click on initial tune parameters enter prop size and battery type, if you are using mission planner. I recommend mission planner. Reduce p , I , d (keep p and i equal)  of both roll and pitch till you get a stable hover in stabilize flight mode. Better use a telemetry radio instead of connecting a laptop to it every time. Reduce p and I in larger steps than D. All these value can be found in extended tuning tab of mission planner. Now once you get a stable hover , switch to althold with mot_thst_hover param set to 2. Disable it after a 30 second flight by changing the parameter to 0. Plug in the hover learn value into throttle to accel gains p= hover learn, I = 2*hover learn, then takeoff in althold and switch to loiter. If everything is fine, you can proceed with autotune. Don't use dampers for autopilot, it already has two IMUs damped internally. Square tubes (motor arms) can cause vibration because of pulse from the propeller,  passing over it , better use a round pipe or try notch filtering. Probably, you can't autotune it if the flight time is very less.

The reason that Makita doesn't seem as exciting as other tool brands comes down to their core culture as a high quality Japanese tool company.  They don't rush into anything, they don't jump on bandwagons, and they don't release anything until they think it is ready.  This doesn't mean that they don't make mistakes, or that they don't occasionally miss the mark; but it does mean that their build quality is top notch and when they do release a new tool, it is often a game changer in that tool class.  The flip side is that they release a new model every 7-10 years instead of every 2 years.  They take that time to study how the tool is used and how it breaks so that the next one is better.  I appreciate that they don't try to make the most powerful tool, they try to make the best tool for the job and job rating.  Sure, you can take a Milwaukee and push it till it screams and it will most often the most powerful version of that tool, but it will tear itself apart while doing that. A Makita will just shut off if you start asking it to do something it isn't intended to do.  On their impact wrenches people often complain that you can't slap a too big socket on it and blow it to bits, but the makita will just shut down and tell you "go get a bigger wrench that is meant for this bulldozer, I'm designed for a civic".

E0ZZ-uWKkwU.title: Mechanics React to Shop Pranks That Went Too Far
top_comments: Justin is a twin 😮
Justin has a twin and SANDRO HAS THE VAN!!!!

I worked as a CNA for a while, and me and one of my patients decided to play a prank on the dour old nurse on duty. The patient had a catheter, so I hid the bag on the back of the chair. I got a new catheter bag and filled it up with white grape juice, then strapped it to her leg (she was in on it, and wanted to do it) just like a normal catheter. When the nurse came in to assess her for the am meds, I pretended like I was emptying the catheter into a brand new measuring cylinder. After draining the very uriney-looking juice into the container, I stood there chatting up the nurse, and then casually just started taking sips...

She didn't notice the first one, but the second time her eyes went wide and she shrieked "what the hell are you doing?!!" By then, the patient was convulsing with silent laughter.

We also had a young guy who was paralyzed, but alert and responsive. I asked him if he wanted to play a prank on the oncoming night shift girl, and he nodded yes, and grinned. He was pretty big, so I usually had him in bed and squared away before she came on. That night, I pushed his chair into the bathroom like usual, but left him in it and threw a sheet over him, tucked just to the side so he was hidden, but could still see what was happening. I then went and laid down in his bed and covered myself with the sheet, and put my limbs in the position he was usually stuck in.

When she came in to check on him, she pulled the sheet back and I jumped out. She screamed so loud half of the administration came running down from the nurse's station to see what was wrong. The guy was in the corner laughing his head off and grinning from ear to ear. Lol.

In 2019, almost all of 2019 I was a Homeless Disabled Veteran. BUT, I had a roof over my head as I bounced around from Ohio State Park to Ohio State Park. I had food in my belly, with having my microwave in the trailer, my dorm fridge, my desk with my laptop and internet access. cUJ9NNMvduw.title: Its Beginning to Look Like Home. The Abandoned Tiny Home Project. Lot32 Destination Adventure.
top_comments: Hey brother, retired fire inspector here. You are very lucky that you didn't lose your home to fire. Oily stain type finishes and even cooking oil stained rags  have a known history of self ignition when balled up and packed in a bag or other combustible container. I remember a fire destroyed a million dollar home 2 or 3 weeks before the owners moved in. The flooring contractor was staining real wood floors and trim. His uninformed workers balled up the old stained rags and thew them in a corner. During the night they generated heat , ignited and burned the home down. A metal container for those with a tight lid can usually keep that from happening but I used to tell people to take that can outside and away from the house until they are ready for proper disposal. You can always get more rags pretty cheap. This spontaneous heating phenomenon through oxidation is very real.

As a mother of grown children. I was so worried when you stood on the frozen river. The "bold face lie" made me feel better. You rock Sir, but don't scare me like that again.😂😂😂 The emotional rollercoaster wheeewwww.💜

top_comments:
Long time listener. First time caller.
In our town 7-3/4 is max stair rise. You can also cheat the total rise down, creating a slight pitch to the treads for further savings on the total run.

I find 8" a bit tall for rise height personally.

Enjoying your content, thanks!

The only thing about the stairs you may not have (or maybe did?) take into account is if your stairs are not up to code (especially if intentional) and someone injures themselves on them, insurance may not cover you.  Since this is a rental/AirBnB, this could be a massive legal and financial liability. Especially since these videos are in the public domain and you have admitted on more than one occasion that you are only using the current stairs "to fool the code inspectors" or to "pass code".  Protect yourself, your family, and your future as a Youtuber, please.

In Europe we use something called the "stair formula". The rule is that "2x riser height plus 1x tread depth equals 65 cm / 26 inch" (which is the length of a human step). This means that you can make stairs as steep as you want, but when the riser height increases, the tread depth has to decrease accordingly. Applying this rule will result in comfortable stairs, no matter how lazy or steep.
The way you typically use this formula is that you take the distance from floor to floor, divide it by the number of steps (an integer value) which gives you the riser height. Then use the stair formula to determine the tread depth.
For example when the floor to floor height is 10 foot (120 inch) you can do 15 treads (the upper floor counts as one), resulting in a riser height of 8" and therefore a tread depth of 10". But for a steeper stair (maybe space is limited) you can decrease the number of treads to 12 where each step has a rise of 10" and a tread depth of 6". Both examples will work well, but the second one is getting close to a ladder. Of course when you need things like 11 or 13 steps, going metric and using a calculator makes this all much easier.
I've never seen this rule applied in North America. But especially outside sidewalks have often horrible stairs that make you stumble.

9cd09Y-hgyw.title: Bismarck’s Final Battle - The Bismarck Part 4
top_comments: Thanks for joining us on this naval adventure. Where should we set course for the next miniseries? Join the Timeghost Army to keep the wind in our sails!

My father was onboard HMS Dorsetshire during the Bismarck episode. He took part in the rescues of the 86 survivors picked up by Dorsetshire, before the rescue efforts had to be abandoned. One of the men he helped onboard, a member of turret "Dora's" gun house crew named Friedrich Junghans, gave dad his "erkennungsmarke" or dogtag in gratitude. Post war dad tried to return the dogtag to Friedrich but was unable to trace him. He later found out that Friedrich had died in Los Angeles USA in 1973, so in 1993 dad donated Friedrich's dogtag to the "Merseyside Maritime Museum" in Liverpool UK where it is still on display to this day.

The story of the Polish ship reminds of a friend I had long ago. I saw him on remembrance Sunday wearing his RAF gear and some medals, I recognised most but not one that was huge and shiny, he told me it was, "A coffee tin lid". I found out later where he got it. After spending time flying Lancasters he was swapped to teaching Poles how to fly, he said it was the scariest thing he ever did because they HATED the NAZI, (quite understandably I thought) and would fly at them no matter what. It was quite the statement considering he won the medal, which was Polish, for flying Polish spies into occupied Poland in a little Lysander aircraft. Thank you for reminding me of my friend.

As a dental professional of 25 years we see younger and younger kids asking about teeth bleaching when it really isn't necessary all because society says you have to have insanely white teeth that look like tic tacs. Can we normalise naturally white teeth which can have a very slightly yellowish hue, which is totally NORMAL? I talk more people out of bleaching to save their money than to promote it, the exposure to social media and people constantly seeing influencers and celebrities with bad veneers and crowns which are very unnatural and insanely white. I have had to pull out the shade guide and they are always surprised when I show them how white their teeth actually are.
Normal brushing/flossing and low staining foods with a hygiene appointment every 6 months is sufficient, imo. It does make me sad to hear young children asking about bleaching when they have naturally white teeth already, societal 'norms' are changing and there are a lot of dentist making money from people being insecure about their natural coloured teeth.

As a dental assistant, you're spot on! Another thing I would add to reduce sensitivity is not just brush with Sensodyne (or any equivalent with potassium nitrate) but after brushing, get a paper towel, dry your teeth, then rub some Sensodyne on them. Concentrate on the areas you're most sensitive - gum recession, etc. Leave it on for like 10 min then spit it out. We tell our patients to do this every day at least 2 weeks before starting any whitening treatment, as well as in between sessions.

kQClCrUtyVY.title: PRIOR REPAIR ATTEMPT on this Anbernic RG 40XXV | Can I FIX It?
top_comments: Cheap USB-C devices usually don't work with USB-C to USB-C cables. So my suggestion is to always use a USB-A to C for testing because they will always supply 5V even if nothing is plugged in.

As other people have already written, your new USB-C to USB-C cable might be perfectly fine. The problem is that USB-C needs 5.1 kOhm resistors from both CC1 and CC2 to GND to signal to the power source that a device is connected that needs power. I have not seen those resistors in the device. They are usually close to the USB-C port. USB-A to USB-C cables will work fine. The USB-A output port of the power source does not have any CC pins and requires no such resistors. It will use other means to determine the power requirements of connected devices.

u8N1YJHqskw.title: Why Young and Elderly People Experience Death Differently
top_comments:
My 17 year old grandson was in a roll over accident that left him as a quadriplegic. He only had control of his body from his head to his shoulders. But not down to his feet. He could move his arm but his fingers were gnarled. His brain functioned normally as he could speak and think. Some times I would sneak into his room at night and find him weeping. This broke my heart to see him looking out the window at other PPL doing what he should have been doing. We talked many a time about things.

He would say, " grandpa please get me some weed or even a bottle of crown to help ease my emotional pain . At first I would tell him that doesn't help. But after awhile I could not stand to see him suffer. The alcohol and weed helped him through a lot of pain I knew he was emotionally feeling.

I've been criticized for this on numerous occasions. But I felt his pain and gave him what he wanted. He passed 10 days before his 20th birthday. But he died peacefully after his spinal cord injury. I don't regret my actions. I was told he would die young by doctors. I know where his Spirit went as we talked about the after life and he gave his heart to the Lord. He has been relieved from his suffering which brings me peace. But I cry a lot as I miss him dearly. But the hope I have is that we will meet again at the resurrection. God rest his soul.

The biggest issue with Beeching was the attitude of BR (and the governments of the time) to the axed lines. It wasn't enough to just close the lines, they had to be destroyed immediately as well. It was as if they didn't want to permit the possibility that they could be proved wrong. Track was ripped up and scrapped, no one was allowed to buy lines to operate privately, land was sold for development. This was the greatest error. Deciding to close unprofitable lines was understandable given the way things looked at the time. Making sure they could never be reopened if the world changed was the true crime.

Beeching was commissioned to deliver exactly what the government of the day wanted all along, they wanted a reduction in active railways, and Beeching was the useful "scapegoat" to deflect attention away from the Government to get exactly that.

QKyEJeEAu50.title: THIS is the Spider Bite to Worry About - The Sydney Funnel Web
top_comments: What other venomous creatures should we investigate? Let me know in the replies!

As a kid in the seventies I lived in the outer suburbs of Newcastle 2 hours north of Sydney. We had an inground pool and I would check the bottom of the pool every morning. I would find two or three Funnel Webs every week. They looked dead until you scooped them out and placed them on the deck. After several minutes they would slowly come to life. I would place them in a jar and take them to a nearby ambulance station and they would then send them on to Sydney Wildlife Park where they were milked for their venom to produce antivenom. Caught hundreds over the years I was there.

Lived in Sydney all my life. in 1963 I was helping my dad in the garden and I was bitten by one that I accidentally walked on. 60 years later I can remember the pain on my ankle. XAmgBsm5B4Y.title: HDMI vs DisplayPort for PC Gaming
top_comments: Different versions support different resolutions, hertz ratings, bandwidth, etc.
If your monitor comes with an hdmi and display port use the display port because it will most likely be able to support your monitors native resolution and refresh rate

Do note that Display Port is an open standard, while HDMI is not. HDMI's trademark holders (is that the right term?) get a % from all sells of HDMI products (cables, monitors, GPUs, ...) and actively gatekeep technology advancements (for example forbidding AMD for publishing open source GPU drivers).

Simply for ideological reasons I'd go for display port of possible :)

iK1ZZInYRHY.title: Amazon removes your right to download Kindle books
top_comments:
I had no intention of making two anti-Amazon videos in a row. I didn't even want to make another video about Amazon, as I'd like to focus on philosophical ideas and great books. But this news is time-sensitive, so I wanted to make a video right now to get the word out.

Look up Calibre and guides for removing DRM. Look for alternative ereaders. Buy physical media. Support local booksellers.

EDIT: There are some recurring questions in the comments. I can't address them all, but here are some thoughts.

Question: What is DRM?

DRM stands for Digital Rights Management. It is software that limits how you can use a digital asset. It the case of Kindles, DRM locks you into the Kindle ecosystem. It also helps to prevent piracy. This is the crux of the issue: in order to prevent piracy, companies restrict how you can use what you buy.

Question: Why not just pirate?

I want to support authors and artists.

Question: Does this affect your ability to read books on your Kindle or on a Kindle app?

No. This prevents you from downloading the files onto a folder on your computer, which you can currently do in order to save a local copy (or to use a program like Calibre to strip the DRM).

Question: Is it legal to remove DRM?

I am not a lawyer. I said in the video that to the best of my knowledge it was legal (thinking here only about using the content for personal use), but obviously the law is complex and varies by jurisdiction. You'll want to do your own research before taking any action.
My wife asked for a Kindle for Christmas, and I did some research on them and their competitors and how they manage  your purchases. Long story short: she's really been enjoying her Kobo.
If buying isn’t owning then pirating isn’t stealing.

I 100% agree with you that the "Doppler effect" explanation of sonic booms is misleading. When I give presentations, I like to start out with the Doppler effect explanation and then suddenly ask, "Well, what if it doesn't make any sound? Does it still make a sonic boom?" top_comments: Inertal guidance with surfacing now and then for recalibration by GPS could be an option for the guidance system

You could simply resurface periodically to get GPS position and use that position as a starting point with water velocity and compass bearing (magnetic field is not impeded by water) for relative motion. Obviously sea currents are a thing, so while surfaced, turn off propulsion and measure the velocity to get a sea current vector. Use this measurement to offset derived location.

For turning you should use rudders not fins, ie. place them after the propeller. That way you get a sort of thrust vectoring.

Will be on the lookout for stuff like this, great video as always Dave.
My favorite thing about your video's: as knowledgeable as you are, youre not ashamed or afraid to ask for help when you run into new problems. Never letting your ego get in the way like many would

As a tech, we tend to teardown to point of failure - nothing further. Anything further is wasted time and $$ being flatrate. Most of the time, we’re ripping the pan off anyways to get the crank unseized, and that’s far enough for us and GM. Great find and thank you for doing these though, as they’re insightful. I’ve done at least 20 of these L87s, and a handful of LT1/LT4s for this failure. I’ve had a few L82/L84 with rod issues and ringland issues with <20k too. Quality left out of seemingly nowhere.
